# `std.ui.primitives` — UI primitive extern defs

The boundary functions between `.ssc` widget code and the JVM/JS runtime.
All other `std/ui/*.ssc` files import from here; user code rarely imports
this file directly.

```scalascript
opaque type Signal[T]    = Any
opaque type View         = Any
opaque type EventHandler = Any

// ── Reactive ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// Generic T resolved at runtime by the default value's shape.
extern def signal[T](name: String, default: T): Signal[T]

// seedSignal — writable String signal seeded from another String signal.
// Copies source while pristine; inputChange/setSignal writes mark it dirty.
extern def seedSignal(name: String, source: Signal[String]): Signal[String]

// ── DOM construction ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// attrs/events values decoded by shape — see spec §"Encoding Map[String,Any]".
extern def element(
  tag:      String,
  attrs:    Map[String, Any],
  events:   Map[String, Any],
  children: List[View]
): View

// ── Non-element View shapes ───────────────────────────────────────────────
extern def textNode(s: String): View
extern def signalText[T](s: Signal[T]): View
extern def showSignal(cond: Signal[Boolean], whenTrue: View, whenFalse: View): View
extern def fragment(children: List[View]): View
extern def forKeyedView[A](items: Signal[List[A]], key: A => String, render: A => View): View

// selectFromView — a <select> whose <option> children track `items`
// reactively (specs/std-ui-select.md § "Reactive options (selectFrom)").
// Unlike forKeyedView, this owns the WHOLE <select> element (attrs, events,
// AND the option children) rather than being embedded as a generic child:
// <select>'s HTML content model only allows <option>/<optgroup>/<hr>, so
// forKeyedView's generic <span data-ssc-key> row wrapper would be silently
// dropped by the browser's "in select" HTML parsing, losing the key. `key`
// gives each item a stable identity for reconciliation (same convention as
// forKeyedView's own `key`); `optionFn` maps each item to the (value, label)
// pair the base `select()` takes statically; `style` is the pre-computed
// CSS string (lower.ssc computes it the same way SelectNode does).
extern def selectFromView[A](items: Signal[List[A]], key: A => String,
                             optionFn: A => (String, String), selected: Signal[String],
                             style: String, placeholder: String, disabled: Boolean): View

// ── Event handler constructors ────────────────────────────────────────────
// SetSignalLiteral — JS-translatable; use instead of a raw closure for
// buttons and links whose click must set a signal to a literal value.
extern def setSignal[T](s: Signal[T], v: T): EventHandler

// inputChange — wires a text input's onChange to update a String signal.
extern def inputChange(s: Signal[String]): EventHandler

// toggleSignal — wires a checkbox's onChange to flip a Boolean signal.
extern def toggleSignal(s: Signal[Boolean]): EventHandler

// ── Derived signals ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// eqSignal: equality guard — used by router to show/hide routes.
// JS emitter maps jsName "__eq__" pattern to a computed boolean ref.
extern def eqSignal[T](s: Signal[T], value: T): Signal[Boolean]

// hashSignal: tracks window.location.hash (empty string on JVM).
// React emitter wires "__hash__" to a hashchange listener.
extern def hashSignal(): Signal[String]

// computedSignal: derives a String signal from a thunk that reads other
// signals. Re-evaluates automatically whenever a dependency changes.
// Use to assemble composite values (e.g. JSON body) from individual fields.
extern def computedSignal(f: () => String): Signal[String]

// Internal component ownership region. Public component(...) keeps returning N.
extern def componentScope[N](scopeId: String, body: () => N): N

// ── Output ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
extern def emit(tree: View, outDir: String): Unit
// `extraCss` (optional) is appended to the base template LAST (so it wins) — e.g.
// `serve(view, 8080, "body{background:#111827}")` to set the page canvas the base template
// hardcodes to #fff. The runtime already threads a 3rd extraCss arg + a ${extraCss} template
// slot; the default keeps the common `serve(view, port)` form. A NAMED overload would break the
// JS extern shim (two `const serve` → duplicate-identifier), so this is one defaulted extern.
extern def serve(tree: View, port: Int, extraCss: String = ""): Unit

// ── Fetch primitives (std/ui-fetch-plugin) ───────────────────────────────
// emptyHeaders — default no-op headers Signal; value is always "".
extern def emptyHeaders: Signal[String]

// fetchUrlSignal — GET url on mount + whenever refreshTick increments.
// headers: JSON-object Signal read at fetch time (e.g. {"Authorization":"Bearer …"}).
extern def fetchUrlSignal(name: String, url: String, refreshTick: Signal[Int],
                          headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): Signal[String]

// fetchUrlSignalTo — like fetchUrlSignal but the URL is a Signal[String] resolved at
// fetch time, re-fetching whenever it changes (a filter/branch switch), e.g.
// `fetchUrlSignalTo("commits", urlSig, tick)` where
// `urlSig = computedSignal(() => base + "/commits?branch=" + branchSig())`.
// The read-side counterpart of fetchActionTo. (A plain fetchUrlSignal bakes its `url`
// String at render time, so a dependent signal change never re-fetches.)
extern def fetchUrlSignalTo(name: String, urlSig: Signal[String], refreshTick: Signal[Int],
                            headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): Signal[String]

// fetchStreamSignal — POST `url` on mount + whenever `tick` increments, with the
// current `body` signal value as the request body (Content-Type application/json),
// then STREAM the response body (const reader = r.body.getReader()) into the signal,
// setting the ACCUMULATED decoded text so far on EACH chunk — so a consumer bound to
// the signal sees it grow token-by-token (OpenAI-style SSE token streams; the raw
// decoded bytes are accumulated verbatim, NOT parsed as SSE). On stream end the final
// accumulated value stays; on error the last-good value is retained (like fetchUrlSignal).
extern def fetchStreamSignal(name: String, url: String, body: Signal[String], tick: Signal[Int],
                             headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): Signal[String]

// intervalTick — an Int signal that auto-increments every `ms` milliseconds (via
// setInterval in the JS runtime). Initial value 0. Use it to auto-poll a
// fetchUrlSignal: `fetchUrlSignal(..., intervalTick("t", 5000))`.
extern def intervalTick(name: String, ms: Int): Signal[Int]

// fetchAction — on click: POST/PUT/DELETE url with body signal value,
// then increment onSuccessTick so fetchUrlSignal consumers re-fetch.
// headers: JSON-object Signal read at click time.
extern def fetchAction(method: String, url: String, body: Signal[String], onSuccessTick: Signal[Int],
                       headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): EventHandler

// fetchActionTo — like fetchAction but the URL is a Signal[String] resolved at
// click time, for path-id endpoints whose id is a runtime selection, e.g.
// `fetchActionTo("POST", docUrlSig, emptyBody, tick)` where
// `docUrlSig = computedSignal(() => baseUrl + "/documents/" + selectedSig() + "/submit")`.
// (A plain `fetchAction` bakes its `url` String at render time.)
extern def fetchActionTo(method: String, urlSig: Signal[String], body: Signal[String], onSuccessTick: Signal[Int],
                         headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): EventHandler

// incSignal — on click: increment an Int signal by 1.
extern def incSignal(s: Signal[Int]): EventHandler

// fetchActionClear — like fetchAction but resets the body signal to "" on success.
extern def fetchActionClear(method: String, url: String, body: Signal[String], onSuccessTick: Signal[Int],
                            headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): EventHandler

// ── Scope B.4: structured onSuccess effects ────────────────────────────────────
// Effect descriptors passed to fetchActionWith; the browser runs them in order on
// a 2xx response. onBumpTick → increment a tick (re-fetch); onSetSignal → set a
// signal to a literal; onNavigate → set the location hash (route);
// onOpenJson → parse the 2xx response body as JSON and location.href the
// urlTemplate with :value replaced by the named field (open-what-you-created).
extern def onBumpTick(tick: Signal[Int]): Any
extern def onSetSignal[T](sig: Signal[T], value: T): Any
extern def onNavigate(path: String): Any
extern def onOpenJson(urlTemplate: String, field: String): Any

// formBody — a request-body source (Scope B.4+) assembled at submit from the named
// field signals into a flat JSON object; pass it as the `body` of fetchActionWith
// for declarative form submits (browser-assembled).  Each entry is either a bare
// field name (the JSON key equals the signal id) or a `(jsonKey, signalId)` tuple
// when the wire key must differ from the signal id, e.g.
// `formBody([("customerName", "customer"), "amount"])` →
// `{ "customerName": <customer>, "amount": <amount> }`.
extern def formBody(fields: List[Any]): Any

// fetchActionWith — like fetchAction but with a structured onSuccess effect list
// instead of a single tick.  Registers as an ordinary action (contentAction).
// `body` is a Signal[String] or a `formBody(...)` descriptor.
extern def fetchActionWith(method: String, url: String, body: Any,
                           onSuccess: List[Any], headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): EventHandler

// fetchCaptureAction — like fetchAction, but on a 2xx writes the RESPONSE BODY
// into the `into` signal (instead of discarding it), then increments
// onSuccessTick.  The seam for POST flows whose reply you must read — e.g. a
// `/login` that returns a minted bearer token:
//   val resp = signal("loginResp", "")
//   button("Log in", fetchCaptureAction("POST", "/login", creds, resp, tick, hdrs))
//   // then: jsonValue(resp()).get("token").asString  (see fetchJsonCaptureAction)
extern def fetchCaptureAction(method: String, url: String, body: Signal[String],
                              into: Signal[String], onSuccessTick: Signal[Int],
                              headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): EventHandler

// ── DataTable primitives ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
// fieldColumn — descriptor for a data column: title shown in header + dot-path field.
// Optional editAction (a rowEditAction) enables inline cell editing for this column.
extern def fieldColumn(title: String, fieldPath: String, align: String = "",
                       editAction: Any = null): Any

// rowDeleteAction — per-row delete button: POSTs idField value, bumps tick.
extern def rowDeleteAction(url: String, idField: String, tick: Signal[Int],
                           headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): Any

// rowPostAction — per-row custom action: POSTs/PUTs a Field/WholeRow/Fields
// payload (a String remains shorthand for Field), then bumps tick on 2xx.
// url supports path templating: '/:field' segments are replaced with the row's
// (URL-encoded) field value at click time — e.g. "/api/paid/:id" (mirrors
// rowLink's ':value'). Unknown fields stay verbatim.
extern def rowPostAction(label: String, method: String, url: String, payload: Any,
                         tick: Signal[Int], headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): Any

// rowLinkAction — per-row navigate/select: writes item.fieldPath into signal on click.
extern def rowLinkAction(label: String, signal: Signal[String], fieldPath: String): Any

// rowEditAction — inline cell-edit descriptor: on blur/Enter fires method to url with
// JSON body {idField: row[idField], fieldPath: newValue}, bumps tick on 2xx.
extern def rowEditAction(method: String, url: String, idField: String,
                         tick: Signal[Int], headers: Signal[String] = emptyHeaders): Any

// dataTableView — builds a View.DataTable from a TableDataSource + column/action descriptors.
// Web backends lower to <table><thead><tbody> chrome via DataTableLowering.
// Swing renders natively as JTable.
// Also accepts a bare FetchUrlSignal for the legacy Remote path.
extern def dataTableView(source: Any, columns: List[Any], actions: List[Any],
                         rowKeyPath: String = "id"): View

// staticRowsSource — wraps a static list of row maps into a TableDataSource.StaticRows.
extern def staticRowsSource(rows: List[Any]): Any

// signalRowsSource — wraps a reactive signal into a TableDataSource.SignalRows.
extern def signalRowsSource(sig: Any): Any

// fetchRowsSource — wraps a fetch signal + dotted envelope path (Scope B.3) into
// a TableDataSource.Remote; rowsPath unwraps a non-standard fetch envelope.
extern def fetchRowsSource(sig: Any, rowsPath: String): Any

// ── RowPayload constructors ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
extern def fieldPayload(name: String): Any
extern def wholeRowPayload(): Any
extern def fieldsPayload(names: List[String]): Any

// ── Column kind constructors ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
extern def dateColumn(title: String, fieldPath: String, align: String = "",
                      format: String = ""): Any
extern def moneyColumn(title: String, fieldPath: String, align: String = "",
                       currency: String = "USD", locale: String = ""): Any
extern def statusColumn(title: String, fieldPath: String, align: String = "",
                        colorMap: Any = null): Any
extern def linkColumn(title: String, fieldPath: String, align: String = "",
                      urlTemplate: String = ""): Any

// stackedColumn — two-line cell: the main field value with a smaller, dimmer
// sub-line beneath it (e.g. a model name with its ★ rating underneath).
// An empty/absent subFieldPath value renders as a plain one-line cell.
extern def stackedColumn(title: String, fieldPath: String, subFieldPath: String,
                         align: String = ""): Any
```
